# The bridge contract (Rust ⇄ Luau)

The single most breakage-prone part of Studio Stud is the boundary between the engine and the plugin. Treat the protocol as one artifact with two implementations. Transport is JSON over HTTP — the engine runs a local HTTP daemon (`tiny_http` on `127.0.0.1:31878` today) and the plugin polls it.

## Rules
- **One source of truth.** The message schema is defined once (in Rust). The Luau plugin mirrors it by hand — there is no codegen, so the two must be kept in sync deliberately.
- **Both sides move together.** You may not change a request or response shape on one side only. A protocol change = Rust DTO + Luau handler + doc + version bump, in one change. Use the `add-protocol-message` skill so nothing is skipped.
- **Version the protocol.** `PROTOCOL_VERSION` and `MIN_PLUGIN_PROTOCOL_VERSION` live in the engine's util module (`src/util.rs` today); the plugin carries `PLUGIN_VERSION` and `MIN_DAEMON_PROTOCOL_VERSION`. Bump on any breaking shape change so the two refuse to talk across an incompatible version with a clear error — not a silent deserialize failure.
- **Wire conventions.** JSON over HTTP; **`camelCase`** field names on the wire (`#[serde(rename_all = "camelCase")]` on DTOs, e.g. `placeId`, `limitSiblings`). Responses use an `{ "ok": true | false, ... }` envelope with an `error` field on failure. Optional fields are explicit; never rely on positional ordering.
- **Serialize at the edge.** `serde` derives on dedicated wire structs (DTOs); don't serialize internal engine types directly — keep an explicit DTO layer so refactors don't leak into the protocol.
- **Backward-compatible first.** Prefer additive changes (new optional field, new message) over breaking ones. When you must break, bump the version and update both sides + the doc in the same change.

## Session mode (edit vs play)
The plugin reports whether Studio is in a genuine edit session or a play/run session on every heartbeat: the 3 s `GET /studio-stud/capture/request` poll carries `?sessionMode=edit|play` (derived from `RunService:IsEdit()`). This is additive — absent ⇒ `edit`, so the protocol stays **v1**. The daemon tracks it in-memory with a short freshness TTL (a closed plugin reverts to `edit`, so writes are never frozen by a stale signal), surfaces it on the `/studio-stud/ping` response (`sessionMode`, `staleSince`), and while a fresh `play` is reported it withholds queued capture work and refuses `/studio-stud/write/{token,validate,preview,apply}` and `/studio-stud/live/delta` with `{ "ok": false, "error": "studio_in_play_session" }`. The plugin also gates these client-side, so daemon refusal is defense-in-depth for CLI/Cursor-originated writes.

When in doubt about a field's meaning, the protocol doc (`docs/usage.md`) and the Rust DTO — not memory — are authoritative.
